No, Ed.  You haven't been orphaned. I've been checking in daily - I miss you guys when I'm gone too long and I worry when one of you doesn't check in for awhile...<br>
just like a mom. Now let's see...I'm 44 and I would guess that your combined average age is about 50...so that means that I had you at the age of about, oh.. negative six...too weird.<br><br>
Paul's right about me sitting in front of my computer (though in my case it's Web TV - I'm computer phobic) and laughing and crying.  Some of the things you guys write get me laughing out loud...what a bunch of clowns.  I have visions of you all typing away madly with your demonic grins and lopsided, dented halos. <br><br>
In reference to your question about PTSD, I read an excellent book written by Patience Mason (the wife of Bob Mason - author of &quot;Chickenhawk&quot;) called &quot;Recovering from the War.&quot;  She interviewed several vets in doing her research and what made her book so invaluable was her list of PTSD symptoms specific to Vietnam Vets - there is a difference.  I was fully aware of the symptoms officially listed under the PTSD &quot;guidelines&quot; that even the VA uses, but there are so many little behaviors that so many vets have had that continually tend to screw up their relationships.  You may find that book both enlightening and comforting.  She intended the book to be for wives and family members, but I think it is a &quot;must read&quot; for all.  If you're interested, I'll give you her e-mail address.<br><br>
ANNE
